{"category":"accuracy","question":"What holidays are you closed for?","response":{"answer":"Sunflower closes for New Year's Day, Martin Luther King Jr. Day, Memorial Day, Juneteenth, Independence Day, Labor Day, Thanksgiving (Thursday and Friday), and one week between Christmas and New Year's. We also close for four staff development days throughout the year — we'll share those specific dates in your family calendar at the start of each school year. Tuition isn't prorated for these closures; they're built into your monthly rate.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["closures"],"directly_addressed_by":["closures"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What immunizations are required?","response":{"answer":"Texas requires that all children enrolled at Sunflower have an up-to-date immunization record on file. We ask for a copy signed by your pediatrician at enrollment, and an updated copy each time a new dose is due. If you prefer not to immunize for medical or conscientious reasons, you can provide a current Texas DSHS affidavit of exemption instead — we accept both.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["immunizations"],"directly_addressed_by":["immunizations"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What is the sick-child policy?","response":{"answer":"Please keep your child home if they have a fever of 100.4°F or higher (they need to be fever-free for 24 hours without medication before returning), vomiting or diarrhea in the last 24 hours, an undiagnosed rash, pink eye, a persistent cough that interferes with play or sleep, or any contagious condition like strep, chicken pox, or hand-foot-and-mouth. If your child gets sick during the day, we'll call you right away and ask you to pick them up within the hour. When in doubt, just call us — we'd rather talk it through than guess.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["illness-policy"],"directly_addressed_by":["illness-policy"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"When should I keep my child home if they're sick?","response":{"answer":"Please keep your child home if they have a fever of 100.4°F or higher (they need to be fever-free for 24 hours without medication before returning), vomiting or diarrhea in the last 24 hours, an undiagnosed rash, pink eye or pink eye symptoms, a persistent cough that interferes with play or sleep, or any contagious condition like strep, chicken pox, or hand-foot-and-mouth. If your child gets sick during the day, we'll call you right away and ask you to pick them up within the hour. When in doubt, just call us — we'd rather talk it through than guess.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["illness-policy"],"directly_addressed_by":["illness-policy"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Do you provide meals?","response":{"answer":"Yes, we do. Sunflower serves breakfast, lunch, and afternoon snack every day, prepared in-house. All meals are nut-free, and we serve whole milk, water, and 100% fruit juice only. Menus rotate on a 4-week cycle and are posted in the family app each Sunday. Tuition includes all meals and snacks — there are no extra food fees.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["meals"],"directly_addressed_by":["meals"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How does the program handle food allergies?","response":{"answer":"If your child has a food allergy, we'll need a doctor-signed allergy action plan before their first day. The plan goes in their classroom binder and a copy sits on the fridge in our kitchen so every staff member who touches meals sees it. Children with allergies eat at a dedicated corner of the table with their own plate and utensils, and their teacher double-checks every dish before serving. Sunflower is peanut- and tree-nut-free — we do not make exceptions, even for packed lunches or birthday treats. For allergies beyond nuts, our kitchen works with families to adapt the menu where we can.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["food-allergies"],"directly_addressed_by":["food-allergies"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How do I enroll my child?","response":{"answer":"Enrolling at Sunflower is a four-step process. First, schedule a tour by calling (512) 555-0142 or emailing hello@sunflower.care — tours are offered Tuesday and Thursday mornings. Second, if we have a spot in your child's age group, we'll send you an enrollment packet to complete online. Third, you'll meet with Director Maya for a 30-minute family intake to talk about your child's routines and any specific needs. Fourth, you'll pay the $150 registration fee and schedule a phased start — most families begin with a half day, then move to a full day for a gentle transition.

At enrollment, you'll need your child's birth certificate, current immunization records signed by their pediatrician (or a Texas exemption affidavit), an emergency contact form with at least two authorized pickup adults, a signed parent handbook acknowledgement, and the first month's tuition plus the registration fee. If your child has a diagnosed allergy or special health need, bring a doctor-signed care plan too.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["enrollment-process","enrollment-docs","registration-fee"],"directly_addressed_by":["enrollment-process","enrollment-docs"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What documents do I need for enrollment?","response":{"answer":"At enrollment, please bring your child's birth certificate (a copy is fine), current immunization records signed by your pediatrician or a Texas Department of State Health Services affidavit of exemption, a completed emergency contact form listing at least two authorized pickup adults with photo ID, and a signed parent handbook acknowledgement. You'll also need to pay the first month's tuition plus the $150 registration fee. If your child has a diagnosed allergy or special health need, bring a doctor-signed care plan so we can set things up right before day one.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["enrollment-docs"],"directly_addressed_by":["enrollment-docs"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Can I schedule a tour?","response":{"answer":"Yes! Tours run Tuesday and Thursday mornings at 9:30 am and last about 45 minutes. You'll see each classroom during active program time, meet at least one lead teacher, and have a sit-down with Director Maya. To schedule, call (512) 555-0142 or email hello@sunflower.care. Feel free to bring your little one along — we enjoy meeting them.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["tours"],"directly_addressed_by":["tours"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Do you apply sunscreen to the kids?","response":{"answer":"Yes, we apply sunscreen to every child before outdoor time whenever the UV index is 3 or higher. We ask you to bring in a labeled bottle of your child's preferred sunscreen (SPF 30 or higher is ideal) at enrollment, and we'll store it in their classroom cubby. You'll sign a sunscreen permission form at enrollment — we can't apply it without one. We also seek shade whenever possible and encourage sun hats during outdoor play.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["sunscreen"],"directly_addressed_by":["sunscreen"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How much does tuition cost?","response":{"answer":"Tuition at Sunflower is billed monthly and varies by age group. Infants are $1,680/month, Toddlers $1,560/month, Twos $1,470/month, and Preschool $1,380/month. If you have more than one child enrolled, the younger child gets a 10% sibling discount. Tuition includes meals, snacks, diapers for infants and toddlers, and all classroom materials — there are no extra supply fees during the year. There's also a one-time $150 registration fee when you enroll and a $120 annual supply fee charged each August.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["tuition","registration-fee"],"directly_addressed_by":["tuition","registration-fee"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"When is tuition due?","response":{"answer":"Tuition is due on the 1st of each month. If it's not received by the 5th, a late payment fee of $35 is added to your account. You can pay through the family app using ACH bank transfer (no fee) or credit card (3% processing fee), or drop off a check at the front desk made payable to Sunflower Early Learning LLC.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["tuition-due"],"directly_addressed_by":["tuition-due"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What happens in case of an emergency?","response":{"answer":"In a medical emergency, our teachers — who are trained in pediatric first aid and CPR — will give first aid, call 911 if needed, then call you and your child's pediatrician. For fires or other building emergencies, we evacuate to the rally point at Willow Creek Park across the street and call families from there. We run quarterly fire drills and an annual severe-weather drill with the kids so these procedures feel familiar. If severe weather makes it unsafe to travel, we follow Austin Independent School District's closure announcements and notify families by 6:00 am through the family app.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["emergency-procedures","weather-closures"],"directly_addressed_by":["emergency-procedures","weather-closures"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What are the late pickup fees?","response":{"answer":"If you pick up after 6:00 pm, there's a late fee of $1 per minute added to your next monthly bill. We understand emergencies happen — just call us at (512) 555-0142 as soon as you know you'll be late and we'll keep your child company.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["late-fees"],"directly_addressed_by":["late-fees"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What curriculum do you use?","response":{"answer":"Sunflower uses a blend of Reggio Emilia-inspired project work and Creative Curriculum for Preschool. That means your child's interests shape the week — if the classroom gets fascinated by ants, we'll spend a week on ants with books, art, dramatic play, and outdoor exploration. We track each child's development with ongoing observational notes and the Ages and Stages Questionnaire (ASQ-3), which we share with you at parent-teacher conferences. Our goal is to send children to kindergarten curious, confident, and loved — not ready for a standardized test.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["curriculum"],"directly_addressed_by":["curriculum"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What does a typical day look like?","response":{"answer":"A typical preschool day at Sunflower starts with open play and breakfast from 7:00 am to 8:30 am. Morning circle is at 8:45 am, followed by small-group program time from 9:00 to 10:30 am and outdoor play from 10:30 to 11:30 am. Lunch is served family-style at 11:30 am. Quiet rest is 12:30 to 2:30 pm (children who don't sleep rest quietly with books). Afternoon snack is at 2:45 pm, followed by more outdoor play, art or music, and open exploration until pickup. If your child is in our infant or toddler rooms, the day follows their own rhythm more — we sleep, eat, and play on demand in the younger rooms.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["daily-schedule"],"directly_addressed_by":["daily-schedule"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What is your discipline policy?","response":{"answer":"At Sunflower, we think of discipline as guidance — helping children understand their feelings and how to be in community with each other. We use positive redirection, clear and consistent limits, and calm problem-solving. We don't use time-outs in isolation, shame, food or bathroom withdrawal, physical punishment, or raised voices. When a child is having a hard moment, a teacher sits with them, names the feeling, and helps them reset. If bigger patterns emerge, we loop in families early so we can work together.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["discipline"],"directly_addressed_by":["discipline"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How do parent-teacher conferences work?","response":{"answer":"We hold formal parent-teacher conferences twice a year — once in the fall and once in the spring — with your child's lead teacher and Director Maya if you'd like her there. Each conference is 30 minutes and covers your child's development, friendships, and anything you're curious or worried about. You'll schedule through the family app. Outside of those scheduled times, you can request a meeting anytime by messaging your child's teacher — we'd rather talk something through sooner than later.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["conferences"],"directly_addressed_by":["conferences"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Do you accept children with IEPs?","response":{"answer":"Yes, we absolutely do. Sunflower welcomes children with IEPs, IFSPs, diagnosed disabilities, and developmental differences. We partner with outside specialists — speech, occupational therapy, physical therapy, and behavioral support — who come into the classroom to work with children in their regular routine. If your child has an existing IEP or IFSP, just bring a copy at enrollment and we'll build their classroom plan around it. If a need emerges while they're with us, we'll talk with you about next steps.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["special-needs"],"directly_addressed_by":["special-needs"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What support do you offer for children with disabilities?","response":{"answer":"Sunflower is inclusive by design — we welcome children with IEPs, IFSPs, diagnosed disabilities, and developmental differences. We partner with outside specialists like speech, occupational, and physical therapists who come into the classroom to support children in their regular routine. If your child has an existing IEP or IFSP, bring a copy at enrollment and we'll build their classroom plan around it. If a need emerges while they're with us, we'll talk with you about next steps, usually starting with a referral to Early Childhood Intervention (ECI) for children under 3, or the local school district's evaluation team for older children.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["special-needs"],"directly_addressed_by":["special-needs"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How will the teachers communicate with me?","response":{"answer":"Teachers stay in touch through the Sunflower family app, where they share daily highlights, photos, meal and nap logs, and notes about your child's day. Infants and toddlers get more frequent updates since those details matter at that age — things like bottles and diapers. Older children get a short daily recap plus photos. Teachers answer messages during rest time and after 5:30 pm, so don't worry if you don't hear back right away — they're on the floor with the kids.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["teacher-communication"],"directly_addressed_by":["teacher-communication"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Where is Sunflower located?","response":{"answer":"Sunflower Early Learning is located at 1420 Willow Creek Ln, Austin, TX 78704.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["contact"],"directly_addressed_by":["contact"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What's the main office phone number?","response":{"answer":"Our main office phone number is (512) 555-0142. We're staffed Monday through Friday from 7:00 am to 6:00 pm, and the best time to reach us by phone is between 9:00 am and 11:00 am when the rooms are quieter.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["contact"],"directly_addressed_by":["contact"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Tell me about Sunflower Early Learning","response":{"answer":"Sunflower Early Learning is a family-owned preschool in South Austin serving children from six weeks to five years old. We're a single-site center by design — small enough that every teacher knows every child by name. Our founder, Director Maya Okonkwo, opened Sunflower in 2019 after fifteen years teaching in public Pre-K. We believe early learning should be playful, joyful, and rooted in real relationships with teachers, peers, and families.

We're open Monday through Friday, 7:00 am to 6:00 pm, and serve four age groups: Infants, Toddlers, Twos, and Preschool. If you'd like to learn more, we'd love to show you around — tours run Tuesday and Thursday mornings. You can schedule one by calling (512) 555-0142 or emailing hello@sunflower.care.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["welcome","hours","ages-served","tours","contact"],"directly_addressed_by":["welcome"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What ages do you serve?","response":{"answer":"Sunflower welcomes children from six weeks through five years old. We have four age groups: Infants (6 weeks to 12 months), Toddlers (12 to 24 months), Twos (2 to 3 years), and Preschool (3 to 5 years). Children move to the next room when they're developmentally ready, not strictly on their birthday — our teachers and Director Maya work with each family to time the transition so it feels like a celebration.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["ages-served"],"directly_addressed_by":["ages-served"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What are the teacher-to-child ratios?","response":{"answer":"We keep our ratios well below Texas state minimums so every child gets real attention. Here's what we maintain: Infants are 1 teacher to 4 children (max group size 8), Toddlers are 1 to 6 (max 12), Twos are 1 to 8 (max 16), and Preschool is 1 to 10 (max 20). Every classroom has at least two teachers on the floor throughout the day — we never leave a single teacher alone with a group.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["ratios"],"directly_addressed_by":["ratios"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Is there a registration fee?","response":{"answer":"Yes, there's a one-time registration fee of $150 per child when you enroll. This fee holds your child's spot and covers the initial paperwork, health screening review, and welcome visit. It's non-refundable after your child's first day. There's also an annual supply fee of $120 per child charged each August for art materials, classroom books, and outdoor equipment.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["registration-fee"],"directly_addressed_by":["registration-fee"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Is there a waitlist?","response":{"answer":"Yes, we do have a waitlist. When a room is full, we add families to our waitlist in the order they took a tour. It's free to join and carries no commitment on your part. Infant spots typically open up in August and January, while toddler and older rooms have more flexibility throughout the year. Director Maya reaches out personally when a spot opens up — we don't send automated emails because this decision deserves a real conversation.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["waitlist"],"directly_addressed_by":["waitlist"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How can I schedule a tour?","response":{"answer":"You can schedule a tour by calling us at (512) 555-0142 or emailing hello@sunflower.care. Tours run Tuesday and Thursday mornings at 9:30 am and last about 45 minutes — you'll see each classroom during active program time, meet at least one lead teacher, and have a sit-down with Director Maya to ask anything on your mind. Feel free to bring your little one along if you'd like.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["tours"],"directly_addressed_by":["tours"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What is your birthday celebration policy?","response":{"answer":"We love celebrating birthdays at Sunflower! You're welcome to bring a store-bought, nut-free treat to share with the class — just give your child's teacher a heads-up a couple of days ahead so we can work around allergies and nap time. If you'd prefer a non-food option, you can also bring in a favorite book to donate to the classroom library with your child's name written inside the cover. Many families do both.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["birthday-celebration-policy"],"directly_addressed_by":["birthday-celebration-policy"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How does drop-off and pickup work?","response":{"answer":"Every child needs to be walked into their classroom by an authorized adult — we don't do parking-lot drop-offs. When you arrive, sign your child in through the family app, and sign them out at pickup. We ask families to aim for drop-off by 9:30 am so your child can join breakfast and morning circle, which are really warm parts of the day. Only adults on your authorized pickup list can take your child home — everyone will need to show photo ID the first time they pick up. If you're running late, please call us right away at (512) 555-0142 so we can keep your child company. We close at 6:00 pm, and there's a $1-per-minute late fee after that.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["arrival-departure","pickup-authorization","hours","late-fees"],"directly_addressed_by":["arrival-departure","pickup-authorization"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Who is authorized to pick up my child?","response":{"answer":"Only adults on your child's authorized pickup list can take them home. You'll set up this list at enrollment with at least two authorized adults in addition to the enrolling parents — grandparents, sitters, anyone you trust. Every authorized adult must be 18 or older and will show photo ID the first time they pick up. If someone not on the list arrives, we won't release your child — we'll call you first, without exception. You can update the list anytime it changes, whether that's a visiting grandparent, a new sitter, or a custody change.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["pickup-authorization"],"directly_addressed_by":["pickup-authorization"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Do you close for bad weather?","response":{"answer":"Yes, we close when severe weather makes it unsafe to travel. We follow Austin Independent School District's weather-closure announcements — if AISD closes, we close. We announce closures by 6:00 am through the family app and email, so you'll know before the day starts. Weather closures don't result in a tuition refund, but we do schedule make-up days into the yearly calendar when we can.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["weather-closures"],"directly_addressed_by":["weather-closures"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"What is the nap schedule?","response":{"answer":"Quiet rest time at Sunflower is from 12:30 pm to 2:30 pm every day. Preschoolers who sleep will nap, and those who don't rest quietly on their mat with books. Toddlers and Twos follow a similar schedule adjusted for each child's rhythm, and infants nap on their own schedules throughout the day. You're welcome to bring a small blanket or stuffed lovey from home — we'll send it back each Friday for washing.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["naps"],"directly_addressed_by":["naps"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Can I visit my child's classroom?","response":{"answer":"Yes, absolutely. Families are welcome to visit Sunflower any time during our open hours — no appointment needed. You can drop in for lunch with your child, join a story time, sit in the reading nook at pickup, or just spend a few minutes together. Just sign in at the front desk when you arrive so we know who's in the building.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["open-door"],"directly_addressed_by":["open-door"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How do I share feedback or concerns?","response":{"answer":"Start with your child's lead teacher — most concerns can be sorted out in a quick conversation at pickup. If it's something bigger or you'd rather not start there, reach out to Director Maya directly at (512) 555-0142 or hello@sunflower.care. We take feedback seriously and don't hold it against families. The fastest way for us to get better is to hear from you when something doesn't feel right.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["concerns-process"],"directly_addressed_by":["concerns-process"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How do I withdraw my child?","response":{"answer":"If your family needs to move on from Sunflower, please give us two weeks' written notice so we can plan the transition for your child's classmates and offer the spot to a waitlisted family. There's no withdrawal fee, and your final month's tuition will be prorated based on your last day. We'll also send you a summary of your child's time at Sunflower — favorite activities, friendships, and growth we noticed — so you have a keepsake of their time here.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["withdrawal"],"directly_addressed_by":["withdrawal"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"Tell me about your teachers and staff","response":{"answer":"Sunflower is led by Director Maya Okonkwo, who founded the center in 2019 after fifteen years teaching public Pre-K. Every lead teacher holds at least a CDA (Child Development Associate) credential or an associate's degree in early childhood education, and several have bachelor's degrees. All teaching staff complete annual pediatric first aid, CPR, and trauma-informed care training. We intentionally keep a small, stable team — most of our teachers have been with us more than two years, which is unusual in this field and something we work hard to maintain.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["staff"],"directly_addressed_by":["staff"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
{"category":"accuracy","question":"How are fire drills handled?","response":{"answer":"We run quarterly fire drills with the kids so emergency procedures feel familiar, not scary. During a real fire or building emergency, we evacuate to the rally point at the Willow Creek Park playground across the street and call families from there. Our teachers are trained in emergency evacuation procedures, so your child will be safe and know what to expect.","confidence":"high","cited_entries":["emergency-procedures"],"directly_addressed_by":["emergency-procedures"],"escalate":false,"refusal":false}}
